Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems of overweight, where overweight affects 9% of the school population and obesity 5%.
Obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, current research shows.
It re-demonstrates the importance of the environment where one grows for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obsessed children feed on sausages at least twice as often as children from normal weight families.
For dinner, more than 19% of the obese had eaten chips the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence."
In families of overweight children there is no habit of playing sports, which is applicable to most current families, where only 15% of children answered that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 children from Basic Education in all of Czechia.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a coincidence", which supports the General Health Insurance Company and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th year.
A proper diet and enough exercise in the family are determining factors, which significantly decrease the number of children who are overweight and even obese.
“Only half of the children surveyed responded that they have five daily meals depending on the diet: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack, and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet,” one of the survey results states.
No breakfast but with steak for dinner
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, details are important, which also count, such as having a fixed time for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of school families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, they each have breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find out that in 10% of households nothing is eaten.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that families of obese children consume insane chips much more often.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet soft drinks daily (70%).
Generally, more than 40% of the children surveyed do sports, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make your diet
The next phase of the study allowed the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
“The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15, from the point of view of healthy eating, are far from ideal.”
Among his favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets.
“It’s especially alarming the popularity of sweet soda,” the study’s final report warns.
As a main meal, it takes the pasta palm and closely follows the poultry meat.
Practically, children always reject legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Change to healthy habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
“In the control group of the study participants, who filled out the questionnaire after completing the prevention program “Obesity is not a coincidence,” a major change was made in favor of the principles of healthy eating.
It is striking, for example, when it comes to soft drinks, where many children would begin to prefer regular water.
Children would also more often choose poultry and fish for the main meal in the questionnaire and restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
