Brand story:
The innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were to search for a term that would define IBM’s strategy with great precision, the most approximate would be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet it has been a hundred years since its foundation.
The basis for this long-standing character was laid by the firm’s first chief, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He coined the motto that many of the world’s problems have a solution if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his hallmark, around which the future giant's life will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the foundation of a carefully crafted corporate culture.
“For us, IBM involves long-term thinking, a continuous movement toward the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it remained true to its core principles, but without fear of the changes around it.
That has enabled us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
