IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York one hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave birth to IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
It had inventions such as the famous "signing clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also presided over his supervisory board.
Flint signed the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson ran the company, revenue doubled by $9 million and began the company’s large expansion across continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after almost forty years occupying the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "pécés", which established the standard of computers of the time, came to market as the IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering comprehensive advice and services with high added value.
The strategy IBM has paid for over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not been improved, for example, in relation to transport and city management.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently unveiled the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
In 1932 he opened a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM’R also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe has is in Prague. Also here there is a world-renowned research team that works with voice recognition.
