How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at the time: ?edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time mostly sold trips only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and travel by Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovakians) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at the time, but one had to queue up with a sleeping bag and spend the night like that, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called “promise of change” that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the “politically unreliable people”, who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without exchange guarantees, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired.
The Czech way of travelling has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It turns out in a great paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, the fact that at the currently favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 you could not travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia then.
In the early 1990s, visa waivers were imposed for travel to neighbouring Western European states, prompting a huge surge of short-term visits, mostly to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see enough of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income from that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to take food (canned, sausages, etc.) with them to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it also the average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in demand for travel agencies began, starting in 1997, regularly, to prepare trips using the connections of charter flights, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
In the late 1990s, Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to a huge demand, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries depart every year. This winter will fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than 15,000 Czech kronor per head, including on-site expenses.
