7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Missing Interview Shown In A Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford – distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off as a preview of a series of special projections in the biggest markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonki of flow charts – a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for over an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
By that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively at his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely’s interview was used on Nerds, he said the interview’s originals disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly re-released footage is the basis of Steve Jobs: The Missing Interview, which arrives at Landmark theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose their technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there is great silence between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking accuracy.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely’s questions, pushing him to move faster toward the topics or arguments of greater importance.
Shot before the Pixar era, the iPod or the iPhone, there’s something oddly prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, the anxious dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, it was and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Missed Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
“Through the years in business, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers that they give you invariably are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why they do what they do, in business no one thinks about things too deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs details his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Disconcerted by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made to the eye of good cuber, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that ensured they could determine commercial costs to detail.
On the joke to the Pope:
Jobs recounts the “Blue Box” he himself built with Steve Wozniak – a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and yelling through the public phone and going back a minute later to the public phone next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the U.S. diplomat, the two burst into turmoil just before the pope himself was woken up to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling on the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Shortly after his 20-minute telephone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
She would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for it.
About improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a customer if he could assemble the entire equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went outside and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
About large companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs prophetically envisioned how many industry leaders would stumble on his vision, and lose control of his market share.
"You say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make copiers and printers better, so what?"
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it’s these kinds of people who end up leading companies and the people in charge of the products are kicked out of the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position rots because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s.
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t make the electrons do, the glass does them, the robots do them, the factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end it all comes down to taste – it goes down to trying to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We’ve never been embarrassed about stealing great ideas.
What made the Macintosh in part great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who casually were the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, I might be doing wonderful things in other fields.
