How to spot a lie
A look at the latest headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses of lying to the other.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “picked” with an open microphone claiming to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
Congressman for New York and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a mockery with his denials quickly rebuffed by the irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been instances where teachers have given test responses to students in order to be better viewed in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere 10 to 200 times.
Sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or “the location of lies,” is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: “I have you,” the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been rebuffed.
Liars look into the eyes.
They don’t always stutter, stutter, rub or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, the microfacial expressions, the formation of questions, and the times.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented lies," while women tell more "self-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than people who aren't married (but the lies they usually tell tend to be "unfortunate".
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, look at the subject’s usual behavior.
This is called “creating a baseline.”
It helps to provide benchmarks to then measure changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally hits your foot all the time so you don’t make unfair accusations when you see your feet beating in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal, and nonverbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as warning signs, not evidence of deception.
People who cheat can freeze their upper body as they try to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change their post-interview posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview exhaustion” – that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the tough questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely show that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson pushed his leg to the bottom and used the past time while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: “I didn’t have sex with that woman...Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of “restrictive language” when answering a difficult question: “Well... to tell the truth... as far as I know... as I understand.”
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a wake-up call.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
