Climate Adversity Stopped the Economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, unemployment and informality increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment fell and the economy contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, self-described of the change, which generated great expectations regarding the progress in the economy, but given the climatic adversity at the beginning of the year, there is no growth, but there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the chances of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction in overall economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historical fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost damages, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage in 582,835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent had partial damage, the main crops affected were those of vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography first thousand people, the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 people were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the population being economically active to 5.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
“What is being seen is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market as a result of a restriction of resources by legislation passed in Congress to combat money laundering, since it is not easy for people who illegally grab dollars to work, invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the increase in unemployment also has a demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the state looking for work abroad in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties to enter, and second because entering already has many difficulties to find work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Informality
The analysis of the labor market of Signeño is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being listed as a worker before any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the state’s labor arrears are low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to records from the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income of the workers in Signo was, until September, 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7,375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Combined with the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there was the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Economy from January to June of the state FDI totaled $ 630,697, representing a drop of 87.74 percent compared to the $5.143,312 million registered during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17,280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Faced with the scenario of economic contraction, the State Government requested in July the approval of a loan of 3 billion pesos, the same that would be destined to invest in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2.6 billion pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of the state economy in any sector of debt.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of management capacity of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
“The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, we lacked to align everyone’s effort and above all the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, we hope next year will be much better,” he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events like the frosts at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
“Low economic flow is the product of several events, including frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had,” he said.
Redefine Vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he said that it is necessary to refer the state to productive activities of greater dynamism.
“Overall we have observed that work has been done, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has be unleashed,” he said.
Work to be done
The president of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better directs the efforts of the Government.
“In general terms I would say that the government has been striving to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term program is developed,” he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its conduct of public policy.
“There are elements that allow to say that the government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the government is aware that there is work to be done,” he said.
