Corte validates 'analog blackout' in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional disputes brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog blackout" from 2021 to 2015, by not meeting the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to achieve the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With that result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this remains in force.
The draft judgment, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and law reservation.
In favor of the project, only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and by admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions arranged in it for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers also decided to dismiss the lawsuit filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister-president said he does not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to be prepared.
"I also do not consider that if it did, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector corresponds to the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate, the rectory of the State.
Replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, and results in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing change, he said, would be postponing the benefits of digitalization, which involves a decision in the public interest, which does not only have a technical dimension, “because it encompasses economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic rectory of the State, encompasses a group of powers that the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and has done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, would in any way invade the sphere of competence of Congress, since it is providing in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the legislature, he said.
Possibility of a "vote-by-vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PREP, the difference between first and second place of the governor’s election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality as far as this year's election process in Michoacán is concerned, where according to the data released by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place of the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be remembered, Michoacán did not homologate its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Law, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal deadline for them to enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted their publication within the deadlines provided for in the Law of the Official State Newspaper, which had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local Legislative Power and described as "invalid and illegal" the state president's vote to constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM will be possible the realization of partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, one or more electoral packages, may occur in the event that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of scrutiny and counting in the file of the box or does not open in the possession of the president of the same; or, when there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all the boxes of the election may be made when there is evidence that the difference between the candidate alleged to have won the election in question and the one who has obtained the second place in the vote, is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the representative of the party and/or coalition that nominated the second of the nominated candidates.
The total vote count may also be made if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the supposedly winning candidate and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was second-placed, in which case electoral packages that have been partially counted will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is just 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
