The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country on the verge of economic disaster.
Italian Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A presidential palace statement announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he can form a government.
It is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," he told reporters.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “framework is now well delineated,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, far less than normal, as Italy grapples with a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the battered confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability put the yield on Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employer Confindustria, told reporters after meeting Monti: "We said we would very much support this government."
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, which the crisis forced him to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack by financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women’s organizations.
It will end its round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was named Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescue Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone’s current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before advancing the election.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist it should only be made up of technicians, an indication of his reluctance to deal with a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources noted that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
