Quintet included the country in its two-decade-long celebration tour
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to perform one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It’s been more than 20 years of waiting, but the band says it will also make the dream of playing in the country a reality for them.
This was assured by bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is in the South American wing of its two-decade celebration tour and on Sunday the 20th will make its only stopover in Central America.
That day they will perform at the Estadio Nacional, starting at 7:30 p.m., alongside the Angelina band The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, whose full transcript is in The Nation on the Internet.
For their Costa Rican fans, it is a dream come true that Pearl Jam is going to play in Costa Rica, are they aware of what their fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica once and on vacation; it is such a beautiful country and I think we will be able to stay there for a few days.
So we’re excited to bring our music there.
I ask you because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the previous days.
What do you say to your most ardent followers?
Thank you for staying with us through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people already refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played over the last 21 years have happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We’re really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going to go surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, they are great places to surf; that’s how we found out, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they have been delivering huge shows with a lot of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never played there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's the reason for this?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons we liked those songs and that we may have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting to us and, therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting to people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don’t think any of us imagined that we’d be in a big rock band and having done it for over 20 years ago that felt like a dream.
We keep counting our blessings and are so excited that we can keep making music together.
We all love and love making music.
We’re lucky to go to places in the world we’ve always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of that group of great bands.
We are very close to the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It’s amazing when a movement arises from a group of friends and is something unusual.
From time to time, a band emerges from a city, but it’s much stranger when five or ten bands leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to be friends with all of them still and we’re honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It’s also very strange that a band like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is much longer than many bands last.
First, I think we’re all lucky to still be alive and second, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened up that give freedom to each one to experience.
We trust each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you’re not too on tour because it’s easy to fall into that game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you that you must respect the music and what brought it, without being capricious about being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was a great thing.
We were a band for almost three years and never released a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we’re still really friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started out in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a photo I think about the amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you picked her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we are looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That’s a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to mind.
As a bassist, what are your influences?
There are so many.
Among the first that I think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant even though it is no longer a fad?
I think all of us always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all of them that came out at the same time, and, if there’s relevance now, I think it’s something wonderful because it’s music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever.
At first, his music had darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that may seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs though they may sound a bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed touched me, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there’s some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
Peru:
Fujimori is hospitalized again for medical exams
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted Tuesday to a public hospital to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength he has in his legs, his GP said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including a cancer in the tongue for which he has been operated four times and which remains under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told TV Channel N that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength of its lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said that he does not want it because he knows himself innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, has a weight loss of 18 kilos that have been added to other pathologies such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been held in detention since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Operations of the police.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the death of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official group, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica and made up of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highlight of an extensive agenda of meetings with political and commercial authorities and a meeting with the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, according to the agenda circulated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "suitable for the exchange of information on all political matters between the two nations," the South American country's presidency said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderon to support Uruguay in the incident with France when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultation with its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing since November the G20, a group made up of the world’s most powerful emerging and developed countries, and has been in place with the South American country since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to expedite the completion of tax exchange agreements in order to exit the “grey list” of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), made up of countries that have not implemented all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
On the commercial level, Mexico and Uruguay have been in force since 2004 a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) that has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The mustache plumber passes all three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly over 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which hits stores around the world this month, has been designed from the start to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS handheld system, which allows you to play in three dimensions without the need to wear glasses.
“Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy should work without glasses,” Nintendo’s Spanish press officer Omar Álvarez said during the video game’s presentation in Madrid.
Álvarez indicated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game originally intended for that support", as hits such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesman has argued that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and smooth game.
Álvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook less skilled users.
Once passed, the more experienced players will be able to take a "second turn" at the game levels, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions in order to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This three-dimensional foray of Super Mario also involves the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that did not occur since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo winks to the fans of the saga and repeats the formula of success of previous deliveries, consisting of the mustache plumber will have to go through mined platforms of danger with the aim of freeing Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in movements, environments, costumes and enemies and also a "playable" Luigi.
Colom endorses Portillo’s extradition to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced Tuesday that he has proceeded with the extradition of former Governor Alfonso Portillo to answer in the United States for the conspiracy to launder $70 million.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that demanded Portillo to judge him there.
At a press conference, Colom said his decision was due to the independence of judicial and executive powers, taking into account that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
He said that during his tenure he "did not get his hands on" court rulings and processed all the extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Maroquín will be extradited for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom did is an executive procedure after all the judicial and constitutional instances to prosecute the former president between 2000 and 2004 were exhausted.
According to decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo must be extradited once he has solved his legal situation in Guatemala and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of the Q120 million embezzlement in the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process that preceded extradition, but the Public Prosecutor’s Office appealed and reactivated the case.
