Park or Mountain?
The architects agree on the opportunity of the call beyond controversy about fees
The municipal competition on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-80s, at the height of the now-defunct Barcelona Metropolitan Corporation (CMB), this Administration printed some promotional cards from Collserola.
The pamphlet defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What’s more, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York’s Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park was once again, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented on the north-south axis but up (mountain) -down (sea).
Collserola’s qualification as a natural park leads to this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with wild boars in the role of the Yogi bear.
It was there until, in September, the city council convened a mega-competition consisting of 16 contests for so many other gates to Collserola.
A door leads to the idea of a park, no doubt.
Either that or someone wants to put doors to the field.
The question comes out on its own: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it means to reflect on the city, is the topic of conversation among all the architects of Barcelona.
It’s almost a recurring theme to lay hands on when two members of this ancient caste of elect recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelona architects, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modól and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coastal front "it becomes necessary" to discuss "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerdà, that of the green apples, has not been carried out.
“It starts from the fact that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things for its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex", says the architect for whom the title of "Collserola gates" contains a "lexical trap": one should not think of them "like the accesses to a park, but the delimitation of areas where it is necessary to act".
Modul, as Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, calls the proposal an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers derived from the "uncertainty that is today to project the public space" after the experience lived in the 80s and that had in the area of the Forum "his swan song".
The first fear is the very delimitation of frontiers on which it can be built.
“Limiting something is fixing the next step,” that is, its overtaking.
“We need to think about new urban planning tools, because the current ones [in reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)] can give rise to real disasters.”
More closely to the question, Modol believes that, to simplify, the Vallserola slope "can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona, not", for a purely topographical question.
Modol recalls that there is already a work done by the Collserola Board that "should not fall into a broken sack", although he appreciates the opportunity that the city council offers its guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe conduit that allows architects to enter the debate, but he "doubts" whether it is this technical profile that should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("all right", he points out) that have had to be created: "Architects should be just a tool".
Bayona hints that the answer to the question that gives the title to this piece is complex, because the basis of the contest lacks a global vision of Collserola: "16 cross-sectional contests have been called," he says, "but there is no longitudinal reading, which sees and understands the area as a whole."
This means, at least in your case, that you have chosen to participate in all 16 contests.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors may clash in program and definition with that of the architect next door.
In his view, yes, the city council should ensure that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide, to its full extent, an area of equipment that would effect a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino forgives Jonas Larrazabal and will go free
After 72 days of rooting, the legal representative of the Casino Red granted forgiveness to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey of the process that was followed by alleged blackmail
After 72 days in prison, Manuel Jonas Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of Casino Red grants him pardon before the Second Criminal District Court, which follows a blackmail lawsuit against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, the owner of the Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, made public a series of photographs and videos in which Manuel Jonas allegedly demanded the payment of an economic fee for the Regiomontano municipality to allow the clandestine operation of the bookmaker.
Following the public complaint, the state prosecutor’s office opened criminal proceedings against the mayor’s brother and on September 2 he was arrested and grounded for 30 days.
After four hours before the Public Prosecutor 3 in Heritage Crimes, he was transferred to the House of Arraigo 1, located in the Old Quarter of the state capital.
There he remained for 49 days after he was given a second incarceration order after the Public Prosecutor dismissed the crimes of racketeering and organized crime.
On October 19 he was transferred to Cadereyta prison allegedly for blackmailing the owners of the Casino Red with 1.5 million pesos; however, he remained only a few hours in the medium-security inmate since there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to follow the trial interned in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, he was ordered apprehended by the secretary of the Second Criminal District Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that almost two months after the investigations, enough evidence was verified to determine the guilt of Jonas, such as the collection of 1.5 million pesos to the representatives of the bookmaker in exchange for allowing the operation of the same.
On Monday, Casino Red’s legal representative, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went to the judge José Luis Pecina to ask for forgiveness for the mayor’s brother; so in the coming hours he could regain his freedom.
During the due diligence, the agent of the Public Ministry attached to the Court, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and which of the partners of the bookmaker was the one who granted the pardon, although the lawyer tried to reserve the name.
Based on file 197/2011 legal pardon is granted to Jonas Larrazábal and hereinafter no claim can be filed around the process that followed; in addition, no compensation for damages or punishment will be required.
Following the hearing with the bookmaker’s legal representative, Larrazabal Bretón was ordered to be released immediately at around 3:50 p.m.
The secretary of the court, Jorge Yánez, moved to the prison of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to notify Jonas that he has been legally pardoned and his file will be archived.
He will also notify you of the immediate release order issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people died.
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results released on the accident where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
"Elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the terrain, the blades had contact with trees 25 meters away where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so he had the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that research done in the impact area does not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
“In a search report that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
“The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to carry passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
At the moment, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation can last several months, even could reach a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter operated at cruise speed and that this happened in a soft upward terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations the flight was performed under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports at the AICM placed suitable conditions at take-off, as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico presented layers of cloudiness at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew has sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the radar aircraft's last record coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft wreckage in a small area:
The information available so far allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight and side path.
The pattern of dispersal of aircraft debris makes it possible to assume that the helicopter was impacted on the ground in conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the disaster there remains no evidence of any kind of explosion or fire on the remains of the ship.
The latest research results indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During fieldwork, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above the average sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably disjointed along such a path.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search in a wider area than the congested site, around the accident, no dispersed parts of the aircraft have been found, which strengthens the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Obesity Gene Finding Protocol
Leads Social Security research to discover obesity gene in children and youth; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is leading research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the 'Childhood and Adolescence Obesity Genetics' protocol, which will allow markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the Siglo XXI National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the participation of the population, whether rightful or not, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico West) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue at the Unidad Deportiva Independencia (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Unidad Deportiva Morelos (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day is being celebrated on November 14, the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about physical activity and a family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure intake, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetics (the aim is to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
“The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight a dramatic rise was also observed,” said the specialist of the IMSS.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers rests on the fact that the country’s population differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent Indian American, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in the genes that are associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The direct benefit to the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they present any degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood that he will suffer from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors deliver it in writing to parents, who are told each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high calorie intake, that is, the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tapas, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt of UNAM would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM School of Chemistry, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 patches each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who said that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate, the patches could even be eliminated.
In his lecture A technological opinion of the bumps, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of which are high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
As vehicles travel and effort is generated, this allows the forces to diffuse very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, abounded, a last layer called rolling folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it should have more mechanical force than the asphalt pad and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and diffuse the efforts, the treadmill also requires having the right thickness and care must be taken of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects asphalt binder performance.
When the ground gets wet, the water diffuses inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first one to wear out is the rolling film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not happen instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to at the first signs with proper maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is complied with, to avoid that bumps form frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow to repair the bumps easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
