Introduction of a budgetary "golden rule" in the Constitution
The government of the large Social-Democratic/Christian-Democratic coalition that is in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a budgetary “golden rule” to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible degradation of Austria’s sovereign banknote by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when Austria’s public debt reached 74.6%, a figure well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were to be reduced by one level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay 3 billion euros more in interest each year,” said Michael Spindelegger, deputy Christian Democratic foreign minister.
Austria responds to a request from the Brussels Summit to member countries of the euro area on 26 October: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in a law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian government approximates the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt this type of "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, from 2017, the federal state’s structural public deficit should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The goal is that by 2020/2021, public debt will be reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
