From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris worries about ties between al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the al Qaeda terror group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, over which they had long been suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers already “has the certainty”.
"The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports show that they are cooperating," he said, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two French men in Niger last January reportedly resumed.
Kidnapped at a restaurant in Niamey by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist Axis
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers particularly caught the interest of the researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who stayed for a long time in Maiduguri, a northern Nigerian city, birthplace of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who, supposedly, is close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is progress, but we must certainly wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is becoming increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "supports" had become increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in his operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices of the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressuring Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as an unworthy enlightened community.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin"), incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes itself and demands strict respect for sharia law, while its militants launch themselves into the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are primarily oriented to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were especially active and attacks on police stations increased.
Abuya’s reaction was, as is often the case, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested while alive, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacks Abuya, in particular against the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, spanning from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, worries all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and Al-Shebab Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information".
